2602,AER,1994-12-01,"Risk-Taking, Global Diversification, and Growth","This paper develops a continuous-time stochastic model in which international risk-sharing can yield substantial welfare gains through its effect on expected consumption growth. The mechanism linking global diversification to growth is an attendant world portfolio shift from safe low-yield capital to riskier high-yield capital. The presence of these two types of capital captures the idea that growth depends on the availability of an ever-increasing array of specialized, hence inherently risky, production inputs. Calibration exercises using consumption and stock-market data imply that most countries reap large steady-state welfare gains from global financial integration.",English,NA,NA,84,5,1,1310,1329,NA,Maurice Obstfeld,3896,Male,English,NA,"U California, Berkeley",F21; G15; O41; O16,w4093,1992-06-01,"Risk-Taking, Global Diversification, and Growth","This paper develops a dynamic continuous-time model in which international risk sharing can yield substantial welfare gains through its positive effect on expected consumption growth. The mechanism linking global diversification to growth is an attendant world portfolio shift from safe, but low-yield, capital into riskier, high-yield capital. The presence of these two types of capital is meant to capture the idea that growth depends on the availability of an ever-increasing array of specialized, hence inherently risky, production inputs. A partial calibration exercise based on Penn World Table consumption data implies steady-state welfare gains from global financial integration that for some regions amount to several times initial wealth.",NA,1994,20,1,0,0,0,0,NA,549,4,98,678,73,0.744897959183674,18.2534848484849,21.7841282828283,F,0,0,1,0,0,1,6.91836734693878,0.387755102040816,186,1.89795918367347,"the, of, growth, capital, to",0.0191740412979351,Orley Ashenfelter,21.0592045454545,16.4705808080808,20.4050505050505,17.693802365651,2.78108585858586,2