2849,JPE,1999-06-01,The Structure of Wages and Investment in General Training,"In the human capital model with perfect labor markets, firms never invest in general skills and all cost of general training are borne by workers. When labor market frictions compress the structure of wages, firms may pay for these investments. The distortion in the wage structure turns ""technologically"" general skills into de facto ""specific"" skills. Credit market imperfections are neither necessary nor sufficient for firm-sponsored training. Since labor market frictions and institutions shape the wage structure, they may have an important impact on the financing and amount of human capital investments and account for some international differences in training practices.",English,NA,NA,107,3,1,539,572,NA,Daron Acemoglu; Jrn-Steffen Pischke,1133; 3137,Male; Male,English; Non-English,NA,MIT,J24,w6357,1998-01-01,The Structure of Wages and Investment in General Training,"In the standard model of human capital with perfect labor markets, workers pay for general training. When labor market frictions compress the structure of wages, firms may invest in the general skills of their employees. The reason is that the distortion in the wage structure turns ""technologically"" general skills into ""specific"" skills. Labor market frictions and institutions such as minimum wages and union wage setting, are crucial in shaping the wage structure, and thus have an important impact on training. Our results suggest that the more frictional and regulated labor markets in Europe and Japan may generate more firm-sponsored general training than the US.",NA,1999,34,0,0,0,1,0,NA,416,5,112,680,65,0.580357142857143,15.1579207920792,26.5053871287129,J,0,0,0,1,0,1,6.07142857142857,0.303571428571429,181,1.61607142857143,"the, in, and, of, for",0.0191176470588235,Unknown Journal,35.5597227722773,13.317702970297,15.6047524752475,14.2652926168687,11.4976435643564,20.2,1.78217821782178,0,0,NA;NA,NA;NA,1,0,0,0,0,0,0,0