4295,QJE,2003-11-01,Knife-Edge or Plateau: When Do Market Models Tip?,"This paper studies whether agents must agglomerate at a single location in a class of models of two-sided interaction. In these models there is an increasing returns effect that favors agglomeration, but also a crowding or market-impact effect that makes agents prefer to be in a market with fewer agents of their own type. We show that such models do not tip in the way the term is commonly used. Instead, they have a broad plateau of equilibria with two active markets, and tipping occurs only when one market is below a critical size threshold. Our assumptions are fairly weak, and are satisfied in Krugman's model of labor market pooling, a heterogeneous-agent version of Pagano's asset market model, and Ellison, Fudenberg, and Mbius' model of competing auctions.",English,NA,NA,118,4,1,1249,1278,NA,Drew Fudenberg; Glenn Ellison,1440; 1996,Male; Male,English; English,NA,Harvard U; MIT,R12; R32; G12; R23,w9528,2003-03-01,Knife Edge of Plateau: When Do Market Models Tip?,"This paper studies whether agents must agglomerate at a single location in a class of models of two-sided interaction. In these models there is an increasing returns effect that favors agglomeration, but also a crowding or market-impact effect that makes agents prefer to be in a market with fewer agents of their own type. We show that such models do not tip in the way the term is commonly used. Instead, they have a broad plateau of equilibria with two active markets, and tipping occurs only when one market is below a critical size threshold. Our assumptions are fairly weak, and are satisfied in Krugman's (1991b) model of labor market pooling, a heterogeneous-agent version of Pagano's (1989) asset market model, and Ellison, Fudenberg and Mobius's (2002) model of competing auctions.",NA,2003,30,0,0,1,0,0,10.1162/003355303322552793,75,5,141,769,91,0.645390070921986,14.2504615384615,42.6598846153846,R,0,0,0,0,1,1,5.45390070921986,0.21276595